| Johannes Eisele/AFP/Getty Images Health care Republicans reject Democratic attempts to tighten vaccine laws The stakes are high: The U.S. is experiencing its worst measles outbreak in decades.
All states have mandatory vaccination laws, but they vary in how liberally they dispense exemptions on religious or philosophical grounds.
“What if God forbid someone dies?” said Jeff Dinowitz, a Bronx assemblyman whose bill to limit religious exemptions has nine Democratic co-sponsors — but no Republican backers — in the New York Assembly.
A century of vaccination laws has shown that states with the strictest ones have lower burdens of vaccine-preventable disease.
But research by Neal Goldstein of Drexel University's public health school suggests the issue of vaccine mandates has indeed entered a hyper-partisan landscape.